===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|knowleche|knowleche|knowledge|lang=enm}}, of uncertain formation. The first element is ultimately identical with {{term|know}}, but the second is obscure (neither Old Norse {{term|-leikr}} nor Old English {{term|-lac|-lāċ}} would have given ''-leche'' as found in the earliest Middle English citations). Compare {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|knowlechen|knowlechen|to acknowledge|lang=enm}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|cnawelæcing|cnāwelǣċing||lang=ang}}, {{term|cnawlæc|cnāwlǣċ|acknowledgment|lang=ang}}, and {{term|know}}. Compare also {{term|freeledge|lang=en}}.
* <span style="font-size:85%;">The noun originally provided a counterpart to the now-obsolete verb ''to knowledge'' (see below), but was very early adapted to be the noun equivalent of {{term|know}}.</span>

